---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>In our March 18 update, we implemented a failure-recovery mechanism for the ARCHITECT. When a Simulated Annealing search reaches an energy plateau, the system can now identify the stagnation, halt the process, and formulate a revised strategy. This represents a significant improvement in the system's operational autonomy.</p>

<p>While the engine demonstrated resilience in pivoting, it remained dependent on the underlying LLM's latent mathematical knowledge. To address this, we have transitioned Perqed from a specialized solver into a generalized mathematical reasoning platform that integrates literature retrieval and formal proof techniques into its search process.</p>

<h2>Generalized Domain Support</h2>

<p>The first structural advancement was decoupling the engine from specific combinatorial domains. We transitioned from specialized graph-theoretic solvers to supporting arbitrary mathematical structures, using <code>schur_partition</code> as an exploratory benchmark.</p>

<p>The objective: evaluate Schur Number lower bounds (e.g., S(6) ≥ 537) by identifying valid partitions. This required the ARCHITECT to dynamically generate evaluation functions for arbitrary partitions. We introduced the <code>partition_sa_search</code> node, allowing the ARCHITECT to synthesize JavaScript scoring functions for the high-speed Simulated Annealing loop.</p>

<p>During development, we identified an edge case where the ARCHITECT generated logic that incorrectly reported zero violations due to a missing <code>return</code> statement. We addressed this by integrating an <code>ObstructionDetector</code> into the evaluation loop to validate the integrity of dynamically generated functions.</p>

<h2>Skill Injection Framework</h2>

<p>To move beyond reliance on model weights for strategy formulation, we implemented the <strong>SkillLibrary</strong>. This system indexes over 30 formal mathematical techniques (e.g., <code>bijections</code>, <code>pigeonhole_principle</code>, <code>explicit_construction</code>) within the <code>.agents/skills/</code> directory.</p>

<p>The orchestration Hub now performs semantic relevance matching against the target conjecture and injects the most relevant skills into the model context. This provides a grounded basis for DAG formulation and MCTS verification.</p>

<h2>The Librarian: Literature Grounding</h2>

<p>To further ground the reasoning process, we introduced the <strong>Librarian</strong> component, which utilizes a LanceDB vector store to index academic literature.</p>

<p>During the transition to a standalone <code>bun</code> executable, we resolved a filesystem resolution issue where <code>import.meta.dir</code> evaluated to an internal <code>/$bunfs/...</code> path, preventing database initialization. By utilizing <code>process.cwd()</code>, we ensured the system can initialize its local storage within the user's active workspace.</p>

<p>The Librarian's robustness was enhanced by replacing model-dependent threshold checks with a local <code>seed_literature.json</code> corpus containing over 240 arXiv abstracts across domains such as Ramsey Theory and Razborov flag algebras. This ensures the ARCHITECT has access to relevant academic context prior to strategy formulation.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>The recent updates represent a significant evolution in the system's cognitive architecture. Perqed now integrates search (Simulated Annealing), formal verification (Lean 4), strategic planning (DAG orchestration), and literature-based grounding (Librarian). The result is a mathematically grounded system capable of autonomous research across diverse domains.</p>
`;
---

<BaseLayout title="The Engine Reads Mathematics Now — Blog" activeNav="blog">
  <article class="blog-post">
    <div class="container blog-container">
      <header class="post-header">
        <a href="/blog/" class="back-link">← Back to all posts</a>
        <div class="post-meta">
          <time>March 19, 2026</time>
          <span class="tag">architecture</span>
          <span class="tag">rag</span>
          <span class="tag">llm</span>
        </div>
        <h1 class="post-title">The Engine Reads Mathematics Now</h1>
        <p class="post-subtitle">From graph coloring to universal domains: how we taught Perqed to read academic papers, inject mathematical skills, and escape the read-only $bunfs trap.</p>
      </header>

      <div class="post-content" set:html={blogContent} />
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .blog-post {
    padding: 60px 0 100px;
  }

  .blog-container {
    max-width: 720px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .back-link {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-decoration: none;
    margin-bottom: 32px;
    transition: color 0.2s ease;
  }

  .back-link:hover {
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .post-header {
    margin-bottom: 48px;
  }

  .post-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 12px;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
  }

  .post-meta time {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .tag {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    background: var(--accent-purple-subtle);
    color: var(--accent-purple);
    padding: 4px 12px;
    border-radius: 100px;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .post-title {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 2.8rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    line-height: 1.15;
    letter-spacing: -0.025em;
    margin-bottom: 16px;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .post-subtitle {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.6;
    max-width: 600px;
  }

  .post-content {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.75;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .post-content :global(h2) {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: 1.8rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 48px 0 24px;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
  }

  .post-content :global(h3) {
    font-size: 1.3rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 32px 0 16px;
  }

  .post-content :global(p) {
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }

  .post-content :global(ul), .post-content :global(ol) {
    margin-bottom: 24px;
    padding-left: 24px;
  }

  .post-content :global(li) {
    margin-bottom: 8px;
  }

  .post-content :global(a) {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 500;
  }

  .post-content :global(a:hover) {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 4px;
  }

  .post-content :global(code) {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.85em;
    background: var(--background-highlight);
    padding: 2px 6px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--accent-green);
  }

  .post-content :global(pre) {
    background: var(--background-card);
    border: 1px solid var(--border-color);
    padding: 20px;
    border-radius: 8px;
    overflow-x: auto;
    margin: 32px 0;
  }

  .post-content :global(pre code) {
    background: transparent;
    padding: 0;
    color: inherit;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .post-content :global(strong) {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text-primary);
  }

  .post-content :global(blockquote) {
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    padding-left: 20px;
    margin: 32px 0;
    font-style: italic;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .blog-post { padding: 40px 0 80px; }
    .post-title { font-size: 2.2rem; }
    .post-subtitle { font-size: 1.1rem; }
  }
</style>
